<p>In this project, I used the used cars listing dataset from this <a href="https://www.kaggle.com/adityadesai13/used-car-dataset-ford-and-mercedes">source</a> to build a machine learning model (regression) to predict how much worth if someone wants to sold his/her old car. The dataset contains data of common cars in the UK, and in this project I only used BMW cars data for simplicity.</p>
<p>I'll divide this post in 2 main parts:</p>

<li>Machine Learning Modelling</li>
</ol>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>There are no interesting point here, as both tax, mpg, engineSize, don't have a pattern to looked at. Next, we modified our dataframe by:</p>
<ul>
<li>Change 'year' column to 'car_age'</li>
<li>Use one hot encoding (pandas.get_dummies) to convert categorical variable (model, transmission, fuelType)</li>
<li>Use StandardScaler, which can transform numerical data to have mean of 0 and standard deviation of 1.</li>
</ul>
<p>Here's how the first 7 columns of the data look like after some preprocessing:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<span class="n">X</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df_scaled</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">drop</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">columns</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;price&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">X_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">X_test</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_test</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">train_test_split</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">X</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">test_size</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.25</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">random_state</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">21</span><span class="p">)</span>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Linear-Model-with-Backward-Elimination">Linear Model with Backward Elimination<a class="anchor-link" href="#Linear-Model-with-Backward-Elimination"> </a></h2><p>Now we'll try feature selection with different method, that is backward elimination. The steps of backward elimination are:</p>
<ol>
<li>Select a significance level(5%)</li>
<li>Fit the model</li>
<li>If the p-value &gt; significance level, we drop the feature with highest value. Else, our model is ready.</li>
<li>Go back to step 2 if model is not ready yet.</li>
</ol>
<p>This is how the code and the result look like:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.api</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">sm</span>

<span class="n">regressor</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">sm</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">OLS</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">X_train</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">regressor</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">summary</span><span class="p">())</span>

<span class="n">X_train_dropped</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">X_train</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">copy</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>
